  <h2>Level 5 vs Level 7 — What Actually Changes</h2>

  <LevelComparisonInfographic />

  <p>
    The five core differences between Level 5 and Level 7 work are depth of criticality, word count,
    source volume, command verb expectations, and the strategic (rather than operational) lens applied
    to every argument.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Command verbs escalate.</strong> Level 7 briefs use "critically analyse," "justify," and "develop strategic recommendations" — not just "analyse" or "evaluate."</li>
    <li><strong>Word counts are longer.</strong> Typical Level 7 assignments run 4,000–6,000 words; some strategic reports reach 8,000+.</li>
    <li><strong>Source expectations are higher.</strong> Twenty to twenty-five academic sources per assignment is standard; examiners notice when strategic frameworks lack underpinning literature.</li>
    <li><strong>The lens is organisational, not departmental.</strong> Arguments must address whole-system impact, not just team or department outcomes.</li>
    <li><strong>Format shifts to strategic report or case study.</strong> Management report format from Level 5 is replaced by strategic report, briefing paper, or board-level case study.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Units We Cover at Level 7</h2>

  <p>
    All CMI Level 7 Award, Certificate, and Diploma units are supported, including strategic leadership,
    organisational culture and change, financial management for senior leaders, strategic human resource
    management, leading innovation, and dissertation/research project support.
  </p>

  <h2>How the Service Works</h2>

  <p>
    Send your unit number, assignment question, word count, and deadline via WhatsApp. You'll receive
    a fixed-price quote within one hour with the writer's background and confirmed turnaround date.
    Standard delivery is 5–7 business days; 48-hour express is available for urgent deadlines.
  </p>
